doc.ContractDescription: HETEROGENEOUS (GAS-LIQUID AND GAS-SOLID) MASS TRANSFER, CHEMICAL REACTIONS AND RELATED MULTIPHASE PROCESSES PLAY A CRUCIAL ROLE IN DETERMINING THE CHEMICAL COMPOSITION AND RADIATIVE TRANSFER PROPERTIES OF BOTH THE TROPOSPHERE AND THE STRATOSPHERE. ATMOSPHERIC CHEMICAL AND RADIATIVE TRANSFER MODELS DESIGNED TO EVALUATE CURRENT AND PREDICT FUTURE AIR QUALITY, STRATOSPHERIC OZONE ABUNDANCE, AND CLIMATE ALL REQUIRE A WIDE RANGE OF HIGH QUALITY HETEROGENEOUS/MULTIPHASE CHEMICAL KINETIC AND THERMODYNAMIC PARAMETERS TO PRODUCE ACCURATE RESULTS. IN ADDITION, THE SUCCESSFUL DESIGN AND ANALYSIS OF BOTH LABORATORY SIMULATIONS AND FIELD MEASUREMENTS OF ATMOSPHERIC CHEMISTRY PROCESSES USUALLY REQUIRE RELIABLE KNOWLEDGE OF HETEROGENEOUS PROCESS PARAMETERS. THE PROPOSAL SEEKS FUNDING TO SUPPORT THE P.I.'S ROLE AS CHAIR OF THE NASA PANEL'S HETEROGENEOUS PROCESSES SUB-COMMITTEE, WITH THE LEAD RESPONSIBILITY TO UPDATE OR ADD EVALUATIONS OF CRITICAL HETEROGENEOUS KINETIC AND THERMODYNAMIC (HENRY'S LAW SOLUBILITY) PROCESSES FOR THE PLANNED 2014/2015 DATA EVALUATION AND TO LAY THE GROUNDWORK FOR SUBSEQUENT REPORTS.
